title: For Sale:  FEG Hungarian PA-63 9x18mm Makarov Pistol- Excellent Shape
postcontent:
You are looking at a FEG Hungarian PA-63 9x18mm Makarov Pistol. This gun is in excellent shape! This was my primary carry gun for many years and I need to clean out some of my collection. It will come with a nylon ambi holster, original paperwork, box, and a box of bullets. It only has one magazine! No trades-Cash only! Located in Lenoir City/Kingston area. $200! 

The PA-63 design reflects a compromise between police and military needs.

The safety/decocking lever, located on the rear of the slide, must be pushed forward to disengage the safety. Aficionados of the John Browning-designed Model 1911 or the Makarov PM may find this design unfamiliar, although those with experience using more modern designs such as the Walther PPK or Beretta M9 pistols will find the safety/decocking lever to be located in a similar position.

The 7-round magazine capacity is much lower than many newer service pistol designs.

Due to its lighter-weight alloy construction, the PA-63 handgun produces more noticeable recoil than the similarly sized, all steel Makarov PM, and some shooters may note an increased tendency toward muzzle flip with each shot. This tendency can be reduced by replacing the stock recoil spring with a stronger one, readily available as an aftermarket item.

Many of the objections raised to the PA-63 have to do with its perception as a military service pistol in the tradition of the American M1911A1, the Russian Tokarev, the German Walther P-38 and P-08 Luger, or the Browning High-Power. As its design can be traced back to a German pocket pistol intended for concealed carry in a pocket or under a coat rather than in a holster on the battlefield, these objections are perhaps understandable. After the fall of communism in 1990, the Hungarian army and police units initiated a program to replace the PA-63 with pistols using the NATO standard 9x19mm Parabellum cartridge, first the imported Jericho 941, followed by the domestically produced P9RC, but the PA-63 is still in service in Hungarian law enforcement.

title: For Sale:  Thompson Submachine gun Model 1928 A-1 UNFIRED
postcontent:
This not a replica.  It is an original "Chicago Piano" that was a favorite of  prohibition-era gangsters, law enforcement and WW2 military. To the best of my knowledge, this particular gun was originally issued to the military but never saw combat.  It was in storage during and after WW2 until it was de-activated and made available on the civilian market.  It has only very minor dings from storage.  Complete with internal working parts as shown, Cutts compensator, 50 rd. drum magazine AND 30 rd. stick mag.  Comes with vertical forend AND original military straight forend. Original cleaning rod and oiler are included.  Also included are a custom fancy wood display case plus a fitted violin carry case if you want the "gangster" look . A rare opportunity to acquire a piece of American history.   Go to www.gunbroker.com and type Thompson SMG in the search window if you want to see the value of just a few of the parts for Thompson SMG.

NOTE-  I have received several questions and here are the answers:

CAN IT BE FIRED? No, it has a dummy receiver that does not allow a round to be chambered and therefore it is BATF legal to own.

CAN IT BE MADE TO FIRE?  Yes, if you have a blueprint or a CAD program and access to CNC machinery you can make a functioning receiver. HOWEVER to do so without proper liicensing is a felony. CAD programs and blueprints are available for the  Thompson SMG receiver, but again- think FELONY!

WHY SHOULD I PAY $2000 FOR A GUN THAT CANNOT BE FIRED?  You can buy Thompson REPLICAS for about $1000 that can be fired (semi-auto only).  They are poor imitations of the real thing.  You can also buy a replica Rolex watch for $175.00, but a real one is priced at more than $4000.  If you want a "shootable" select-fire (full auto and semi-auto)Thompson, you will pay $20,000 or more IF YOU CAN FIND ONE, and of course you would need proper licensing to own it.

THIS IS A DISPLAY/COLLECTIBLE GUN ONLY.

This is an open public form where you can e-mail, write,call or fax the ATF and voice to them that you don't want this ammo banned until March 16th. It wasn't even 24 hours after this announcement that price gougers were in full force trying to make a buck off other people with using tricky catch phrases like "own a piece of history" "get it before it's gone forever" "pre-banned" like they have some magic crystal ball where they can see into the future and know it's 100% written in stone it's going to be banned. Don't play into that crap like two years ago when all this hype was happening then nothing happened except a few states encroached on their citizens rights but the majority of the country got to keep it because people stood up and said something. Write, call or e-mail the atf and your state representatives telling them you don't want this. Join the nra if you haven't already. If you stand by and do nothing it will be gone and you won't have any right to bitch about it either. Stop supporting the gougers, flag them, they don't care about you. Stop searching armslist for the lowest price green tips and use that time to write a letter that could mean the difference. 

Informative video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rs-Pu8n_BHg&feature=youtu.be

Petition:
https://petitions.whitehouse.gov/petition/stop-batfe-banning-xm855-ammunition/XrvVh1cj


CONTACT THE BATF:

ATF email: REDACTED

Fax: REDACTED.

Mail: Denise Brown, Mailstop 6N-602, Office of Regulatory Affairs, Enforcement Programs and Services, Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms, and Explosives, 99 New York Avenue, NE, Washington, DC 20226: ATTN: AP Ammo Comments.

Proposed ammo ban letter:
http://www.atf.gov/sites/default/files/assets/Library/Notices/atf_framework_for_determining_whether_certain_projectiles_are_primarily_intended_for_sporting_purposes.pdf

Definition of Armor Piercing: 
(B) The term “armor piercing ammunition” means—
(i) a projectile or projectile core which may be used in a handgun and
which is constructed entirely (excluding the presence of traces of other
substances) from one or a combination of tungsten alloys, steel, iron,
brass, bronze, beryllium copper or depleted uranium; or
(ii) a full jacketed projectile larger than .22 caliber designed and intended
for use in a handgun and whose jacket has a weight of more than 25
percent of the total weight of the projectile.
